{"title_page": "Calamus tetradactylus", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|genus = Calamus (palm)\n|species = tetradactylus\n|authority = <small>[[Henry Fletcher Hance|Hance]], J. Bot. 13: 289 (1875)<ref>{{cite web |title=Calamus tetradactylus Hance, J. Bot. 13: 289 (1875). |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/665451-1 |website=International Plant Name Index (IPNI) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms = *<small>''Calamus bonianus'' [[Odoardo Beccari|Becc.]]<ref name=\"evans\">{{cite journal |last1=Evans |first1=Tom D. |last2=Sengdala |first2=Khamphone |last3=Thammavong |first3=Banxa |last4=Viengkham |first4=Oulathong V. |last5=[[John Dransfield]] |title=A Synopsis of the Rattans (Arecaceae: Calamoideae) of Laos and Neighbouring Parts of Indochina |journal=Kew Bulletin |date=2002 |volume=57 |issue=1 |page=1-84 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/4110822 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"palm\">{{cite web |title=Calamus tetradactylus Hance, J. Bot. 13: 289 (1875) |url=http://www.palmweb.org/cdm_dataportal/taxon/169b3907-b094-4bbf-a19c-9a639e9bb944 |website=PALMwev |publisher=palmweb.org |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n*''C. cambojensis'' Becc.\n*''C. solitarius'' T.Evans, Sengdala, Viengkham, Thamm. & [[John Dransfield|J.Dransf]]<ref name=\"powo\">{{cite web |title=Calamus tetradactylus Hance |url=http://www.plantsoftheworldonline.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:665451-1 |website=Plants of the world online (POWO) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*''C. tetradactylus'' var. ''bonianus'' (Becc.) Conrard, H.Lecomte<ref name=\"palm\" />\n*''Palmijuncus tetradactylus'' (Hance) [[Carl Ernst Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]</small>}}\n\nThis climbing plant in the [[Arecaceae]], or palm, family, is part of a subfamily, [[Calamoideae]], whose members are usually called [[rattan|rattans]] in English.\nIt is native to southeast and east [[Thailand]], [[Cambodia]], [[Vietnam]], south and central [[Laos]], and [[Yunnan]] and elsewhere in southeast [[China]].<ref name=\"powo\" />\nIt grows in evergreen forest and scrub between 100 and 1,000m elevation.\n\nThe conservation status of this palm is likely to be under very little threat, as the species is widespread, common and widely cultivated, though local sub-taxa/varieties might be under threat.<ref name=\"powo\" />\n\nVernacular names include: ''wai krit'' (Thailand); ''re peu'' ([[Alak language|Alak]]); ''wai hangnou'', ''wai hangnounyai'', ''wai savang'' ([[Lao Loum]]); ''kaceck doikanair'' ([[Phong language|Phong]])<ref name=\"powo\" />; ''may'' (common and commercial name for small diameter rattans), ''may tat'', ''nep'', ''may ruot ga'' (Vietnam).<ref name=\"vu\" />\n\nThe cane from this species is of high quality, and probably of trade importance, especially in Vietnam. Vu Van Dung & Le Huy Guang, writing in 1996, argue that this rattan has been cultivated by smallholders around [[Hanoi]] for over 100 years, this is argued to be one of the oldest rattan cultivation systems known.<ref name=\"evans\" />\nThe availability of wild plants of this small diameter rattan was decreasing in the [[C\u1ea9m Xuy\u00ean District]], [[H\u00e0 T\u0129nh Province]], Vietnam.\nSince 1998, there has been local household garden growing, however while manufacturing of furniture and handicrafts has continued, and the Hanoi market has been tapped into, expansion into international markets has not occurred.<ref name=\"vu\">    {{cite book |last=Vu Dinh Quang |editor1-last=Kusters |editor1-first=Koen |editor2-last=Belcher |editor2-first=Brian |title=Forest products, livelihoods and conservation : case studies of non-timber forest product systems |publisher=[Center for International Forestry Research] (CIFOR) |date=2004 |pages=283-94 |chapter=Chapter 17: Domestication of rattan (Calamus tetradactylus) in the buffer zone of Ke Go Natural Reserve Area, Cam Xuyen district, Vietnam |isbn=979-3361-24-7 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Koen_Kusters/publication/272823982_Livelihoods_and_Conservation_Case_Studies_of_Non-Timber_Forest_Product_Systems_VOLUME_1_-_ASIA/links/54fd5c770cf2c3f5242481a1/Livelihoods-and-Conservation-Case-Studies-of-Non-Timber-Forest-Product-Systems-VOLUME-1-ASIA.pdf#page=296 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}\nHousehold items manufactured from the split cane in the area include rope, baskets, pillows and seat surfaces.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15462345}}\n\n[[Category:Calamus (palm)|tetradactylus]]\n[[Category:Flora of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Laos]]\n[[Category:Flora of Southeast China]]\n[[Category:Flora of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Flora of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Flora of Yunnan]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1875]]\n\n{{palm-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|genus = Calamus (palm)\n|species = tetradactylus\n|authority = <small>[[Henry Fletcher Hance|Hance]], J. Bot. 13: 289 (1875)<ref>{{cite web |title=Calamus tetradactylus Hance, J. Bot. 13: 289 (1875). |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/665451-1 |website=International Plant Name Index (IPNI) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms = *<small>''Calamus bonianus'' [[Odoardo Beccari|Becc.]]<ref name=\"evans\">{{cite journal |last1=Evans |first1=Tom D. |last2=Sengdala |first2=Khamphone |last3=Thammavong |first3=Banxa |last4=Viengkham |first4=Oulathong V. |last5=[[John Dransfield]] |title=A Synopsis of the Rattans (Arecaceae: Calamoideae) of Laos and Neighbouring Parts of Indochina |journal=Kew Bulletin |date=2002 |volume=57 |issue=1 |page=1-84 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/4110822 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"palm\">{{cite web |title=Calamus tetradactylus Hance, J. Bot. 13: 289 (1875) |url=http://www.palmweb.org/cdm_dataportal/taxon/169b3907-b094-4bbf-a19c-9a639e9bb944 |website=PALMwev |publisher=palmweb.org |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n*''C. cambojensis'' Becc.\n*''C. solitarius'' T.Evans, Sengdala, Viengkham, Thamm. & [[John Dransfield|J.Dransf]]<ref name=\"powo\">{{cite web |title=Calamus tetradactylus Hance |url=http://www.plantsoftheworldonline.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:665451-1 |website=Plants of the world online (POWO) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*''C. tetradactylus'' var. ''bonianus'' (Becc.) Conrard, H.Lecomte<ref name=\"palm\" />\n*''Palmijuncus tetradactylus'' (Hance) [[Carl Ernst Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]</small>}}\n\nThis climbing plant in the [[Arecaceae]], or palm, family, is part of a subfamily, [[Calamoideae]], whose members are usually called [[rattan|rattans]] in English.\nIt is native to southeast and east [[Thailand]], [[Cambodia]], [[Vietnam]], south and central [[Laos]], and [[Yunnan]] and elsewhere in southeast [[China]].<ref name=\"powo\" />\nIt grows in evergreen forest and scrub between 100 and 1,000m elevation.\n\nThe conservation status of this palm is likely to be under very little threat, as the species is widespread, common and widely cultivated, though local sub-taxa/varieties might be under threat.<ref name=\"powo\" />\n\nVernacular names include: ''wai krit'' (Thailand); ''re peu'' ([[Alak language|Alak]]); ''wai hangnou'', ''wai hangnounyai'', ''wai savang'' ([[Lao Loum]]); ''kaceck doikanair'' ([[Phong language|Phong]])<ref name=\"powo\" />; ''may'' (common and commercial name for small diameter rattans), ''may tat'', ''nep'', ''may ruot ga'' (Vietnam).<ref name=\"vu\" />\n\nThe cane from this species is of high quality, and probably of trade importance, especially in Vietnam. Vu Van Dung & Le Huy Guang, writing in 1996, argue that this rattan has been cultivated by smallholders around [[Hanoi]] for over 100 years, this is argued to be one of the oldest rattan cultivation systems known.<ref name=\"evans\" />\nThe availability of wild plants of this small diameter rattan was decreasing in the [[C\u1ea9m Xuy\u00ean District]], [[H\u00e0 T\u0129nh Province]], Vietnam.\nSince 1998, there has been local household garden growing, however while manufacturing of furniture and handicrafts has continued, and the Hanoi market has been tapped into, expansion into international markets has not occurred.<ref name=\"vu\">{{cite book |author=Vu Dinh Quang |title=Domestication of rattan (Calamus tetradactylus) in the buffer zone of Ke Go Natural Reserve Area, Cam Xuyen district, Vietnam, in Koen Kusters & Brian Belcher, ed, 2004, ''Forest products, livelihoods and conservation : case studies of non-timber forest product systems''. |publisher=[Center for International Forestry Research] (CIFOR) |isbn=979-3361-24-7 |page=283-94 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Koen_Kusters/publication/272823982_Livelihoods_and_Conservation_Case_Studies_of_Non-Timber_Forest_Product_Systems_VOLUME_1_-_ASIA/links/54fd5c770cf2c3f5242481a1/Livelihoods-and-Conservation-Case-Studies-of-Non-Timber-Forest-Product-Systems-VOLUME-1-ASIA.pdf#page=296 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\nHousehold items manufactured from the split cane in the area include rope, baskets, pillows and seat surfaces.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15462345}}\n\n[[Category:Calamus (palm)|tetradactylus]]\n[[Category:Flora of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Laos]]\n[[Category:Flora of Southeast China]]\n[[Category:Flora of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Flora of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Flora of Yunnan]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1875]]\n\n{{palm-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Brunswicknic", "label": "safe", "comment": "see if this works", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calamus_tetradactylus"}
{"title_page": "Mohammed Inuwa Wushishi", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Governor\n|name                   = Mohammed Inuwa Wushishi\n|image                  = \n|width                  = 150px\n|office1                = [[Chief_of_Army_Staff_(Nigeria)|Chief of Army Staff]]\n|term_start1            = October 1981\n|term_end1              = October 1983\n|predecessor1           = [[Gibson Jalo]]\n|successor1             = [[Ibrahim Babangida]]\n|birth_date             = {{Birth date and age|1940|01|01|df=y}}\n|birth_place            = \n|death_date             = \n|party                  = \n|Educational background = \n}}\nLt. General (retired) '''Mohammed Inuwa Wushishi''' CFR GCON (born 1940) was [[Chief of Army Staff (Nigeria)|Chief of Army Staff]] (COAS), [[Nigeria]] from October 1981 to October 1983 during the [[Nigerian Second Republic]].<ref name=armybio>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.nigerian-army.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=41&Itemid=44\n |title=Chronicle of Command\n |publisher=Nigerian Army\n |accessdate=2 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Army career==\n\nWushishi joined the army on 21 April 1961, and attended the [[Nigerian Military Training College]], [[Kaduna]] and then the [[Mons Officer Cadet School]], [[Aldershot]] in the United Kingdom.  He was commissioned as a second lieutenant on 12 January 1962.<ref name=nowa47>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.dawodu.com/omoigui47.htm\n |title=Military Rebellion of July 29, 1975: The Coup Against Gowon \u2013 Epilogue\n |work=Dawodu\n |author=Nowa Omoigui\n |accessdate=2 June 2010}}</ref>\nHe later attended the United States War College Carlisle, Pennsylvania.<ref name=reuters>{{cite web\n |url=http://in.reuters.com/finance/stocks/officerProfile?symbol=IBTC.LG&officerId=1063663\n |title=Wushishi, Mohammed Inuwa \n |agency=Reuters\n |accessdate=2 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nWushishi served as a member of the United Nations Peace Keeping force in Congo in the early 1960s.<ref name=acorn>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.acornpetroleum.com/bod_wushishi.html\n |title=LT. GEN. MOHAMMED INUWA WUSHISHI GCON\n |publisher=Acorn Petroleum\n |accessdate=2 June 2010\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817000440/http://www.acornpetroleum.com/bod_wushishi.html\n |archive-date=17 August 2009\n |url-status=dead\n }}</ref>\nHe was appointed Deputy Commandant, Army School of Infantry in July 1975.<ref name=nowa47/>\nHe served as Federal Commissioner for Industries (January 1975 \u2013 March 1976) and was a member of the Supreme Military Council from 1976 to 1978.<ref name=reuters/>\nHe was Chief of Army Staff (COAS) from October 1981 to October 1983 during the [[Shehu Shagari]] administration.<ref name=armybio/>\n\n==Later career==\nWushishi was required to retire on 3 January 1984 after the 31 December 1983 coup in which General [[Muhammadu Buhari]] came to power.<ref name=nowa47/>\nAfter retirement, he entered business.\nHe became chairman of the board of directors of UAC of Nigeria, retiring on 1 January 2010 at age 70.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://thenationonlineng.net/web2/articles/31442/1/UACN-names-Udo-Udoma-chairman-as-Wushishi-retires/Page1.html\n |title=UACN names Udo Udoma chairman as Wushishi retires\n |work=The Nation\n |date=6 January 2010\n |accessdate=2 June 2010}}</ref>\nHe was also Chairman of the board of UPDC (property development), a director of [[Stanbic IBTC Holdings|Stanbic IBTC Bank]] and MTS first Wireless, and a member of the board of Acorn Petroleum. \nHe received the national Honour, Grand Commander of the [[Order of the Niger]].<ref name=acorn/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{Chiefs Of Army Staff (COAS) Nigeria}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wushishi, Mohammed Inuwa}}\n[[Category:Nigerian generals]]\n[[Category:Nigerian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Grand Commanders of the Order of the Niger]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Chiefs of Army Staff (Nigeria)]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Governor\n|name                   = Mohammed Inuwa Wushishi\n|image                  = \n|width                  = 150px\n|office1                = [[Chief_of_Army_Staff_(Nigeria)|Chief of Army Staff]]\n|term_start1            = October 1981\n|term_end1              = October 1983\n|predecessor1           = [[Gibson Jalo]]\n|successor1             = [[Ibrahim Babangida]]\n|birth_date             = {{Birth date and age|1940|01|01|df=y}}\n|birth_place            = \n|death_date             = \n|party                  = \n|Educational background = \n}}\nLt. General (retired) '''Mohammed Inuwa Wushishi''' CFR GCON (born 1940) was [[Chief of Army Staff (Nigeria)|Chief of Army Staff]] (COAS), [[Nigeria]] from October 1981 to October 1983 during the [[Nigerian Second Republic]].<ref name=armybio>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.nigerian-army.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=41&Itemid=44\n |title=Chronicle of Command\n |publisher=Nigerian Army\n |accessdate=2010-06-02}}</ref>\n\n==Army career==\n\nWushishi joined the army on 21 April 1961, and attended the [[Nigerian Military Training College]], [[Kaduna]] and then the [[Mons Officer Cadet School]], [[Aldershot]] in the United Kingdom.  He was commissioned as a second lieutenant on 12 January 1962.<ref name=nowa47>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.dawodu.com/omoigui47.htm\n |title=Military Rebellion of July 29, 1975: The Coup Against Gowon - Epilogue\n |work=Dawodu\n |author=Nowa Omoigui\n |accessdate=2010-06-02}}</ref>\nHe later attended the United States War College Carlisle, Pennsylvania.<ref name=reuters>{{cite web\n |url=http://in.reuters.com/finance/stocks/officerProfile?symbol=IBTC.LG&officerId=1063663\n |title=Wushishi, Mohammed Inuwa \n |publisher=Reuters\n |accessdate=2010-06-02}}</ref>\n\nWushishi served as a member of the United Nations Peace Keeping force in Congo in the early 1960s.<ref name=acorn>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.acornpetroleum.com/bod_wushishi.html\n |title=LT. GEN. MOHAMMED INUWA WUSHISHI GCON\n |publisher=Acorn Petroleum\n |accessdate=2010-06-02\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817000440/http://www.acornpetroleum.com/bod_wushishi.html\n |archive-date=2009-08-17\n |url-status=dead\n }}</ref>\nHe was appointed Deputy Commandant, Army School of Infantry in July 1975.<ref name=nowa47/>\nHe served as Federal Commissioner for Industries (January 1975 - March 1976) and was a member of the Supreme Military Council from 1976 to 1978.<ref name=reuters/>\nHe was Chief of Army Staff (COAS) from October 1981 to October 1983 during the [[Shehu Shagari]] administration.<ref name=armybio/>\n\n==Later career==\nWushishi was required to retire on 3 January 1984 after the 31 December 1983 coup in which General [[Muhammadu Buhari]] came to power.<ref name=nowa47/>\nAfter retirement, he entered business.\nHe became Chairman of the Board of Directors of UAC of Nigeria, retiring on 1 January 2010 at age 70.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://thenationonlineng.net/web2/articles/31442/1/UACN-names-Udo-Udoma-chairman-as-Wushishi-retires/Page1.html\n |title=UACN names Udo Udoma chairman as Wushishi retires\n |work=The Nation\n |date=6/01/2010\n |accessdate=2010-06-02}}</ref>\nHe was also Chairman of the board of UPDC (property development), a director of [[Stanbic IBTC Holdings|Stanbic IBTC Bank]] and MTS first Wireless, and a member of the board of Acorn Petroleum. \nHe received the national Honour, Grand Commander of the [[Order of the Niger]].<ref name=acorn/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{Chiefs Of Army Staff (COAS) Nigeria}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wushishi, Mohammed Inuwa}}\n[[Category:Nigerian generals]]\n[[Category:Nigerian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Grand Commanders of the Order of the Niger]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Chiefs of Army Staff (Nigeria)]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ohconfucius", "label": "safe", "comment": "Script-assisted fixes: perMOS:NUM,MOS:CAPS,MOS:LINK, EngvarB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohammed_Inuwa_Wushishi"}
